WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.100 --> 00:00:02.400
&gt;&gt; Sasha Dowdy: Welcome
everyone.

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:05.870
Good afternoon, hi.

00:00:05.870 --> 00:00:08.460
My name is Sasha Dowdy
and I work at the Library

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:10.040
of Congress Young
Reader's Center.

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:14.430
This is a special place for kids
within the library for kids,

00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:17.490
teens and family,
everybody under 16 is welcome

00:00:17.490 --> 00:00:20.220
and we're an awesome place
where you can start finding

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:24.030
out about the libraries
treasures and exhibits.

00:00:24.030 --> 00:00:25.570
All day here at the Library

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:28.070
of Congress National Book
Festival we're recognizing

00:00:28.070 --> 00:00:30.240
and celebrating the
importance of reading

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:32.180
and authors and books.

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:35.380
The Library of Congress makes it
seem easy to do this every year.

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:37.580
But the truth is the
National Book Festival is a

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:39.080
huge undertaking.

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:41.720
It's a huge financial
undertaking and it's free

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:44.330
for everyone because
of the general support,

00:00:44.330 --> 00:00:48.340
generous support from our
sponsors and supporters.

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:51.330
Spread the joy of reading
with your gift online

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:54.440
at loc.gov/donate
from the festival app

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:55.740
or when you purchase
books today.

00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:58.660
And now on to the main event.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:01.860
I am here to introduce a
spectacular author Ms. Jewell

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:03.160
Parker Rhodes.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:07.470
Ms. Rhodes, yes, please
give it up for her.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:11.340
[applause] She is a
giant when it comes

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:14.080
to creativity and
creative writing.

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:18.020
She has a degree in drama
criticism, a Master of Arts

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:21.040
in English and a Doctor of
Arts in Creative Writing.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.970
And she is the founding
Artistic Director

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:27.620
of the Virginia G. Piper
Center for Creative Writing

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:29.780
at Arizona State University.

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:33.700
So when you talk about
Creative Writing,

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:35.920
she knows so much about it.

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:37.380
She's overflowing.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:40.610
And she's of course an author
of six books for grownups

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:44.240
and five critically
acclaimed books for kids.

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:48.760
And those are Ninth
Ward, Sugar, Bayou Magic,

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:51.340
Tower's Falling and Ghost Boys.

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:55.650
And Ghost Boys is the book that
we are all here to hear about,

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:58.360
a book about racial
prejudice and the history

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:02.390
of prejudice towards young
black boys in this country.

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:04.450
It's required reading
and it's something

00:02:04.450 --> 00:02:06.520
that we absolutely need today.

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:10.120
So it is my honor to introduce
Ms. Jewell Parker Rhodes.

00:02:10.120 --> 00:02:11.770
[applause]

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:13.960
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: Ok thank you,

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.520
thank you very much, thank you.

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:19.370
I am so excited to be here.

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:24.400
It's like a dream come true
because all my life I wanted

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:26.500
to write for you guys.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:28.600
I wanted to write for youth.

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:33.020
So the fact that I'm doing it
now thrills me beyond measure.

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:37.740
Now I am very proud of my
Louisiana Girl's Trilogy,

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:42.700
Lanesha in ninth ward
surviving hurricane Katrina.

00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:47.300
Sugar in the book, Sugar,
learning that you can be free

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:52.420
and see the whole wide world
and make friends with everyone.

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:57.920
And then Maddy in Bayou Magic
who has to save the plant life,

00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:02.290
the sea life, the animal
life, from the BP oil spill.

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:05.580
I am proud of those
wonderous characters.

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:09.420
But those are stories that I
chose to write for children.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:13.080
But there were two books
that I was asked to write

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:17.560
that each time I said nope,
I'm not going to do it.

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.180
The first book was
Tower's Falling.

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:23.790
My editor asked me
to write about 911

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:27.100
so that kids would have a
chance of what it was all about.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.830
And I said no.

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:31.820
But the more I thought about
it, the more I thought that all

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:34.120
of you who are soon
going to grow up

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:36.410
and be voting citizens deserve

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:40.860
to know how our world has
changed, deserve to know

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:45.080
that we need to have a
country that remains true

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:48.620
to its democratic values
and that we don't change

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:53.330
because of tragedy but instead
we grow stronger and better.

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:55.690
Now Tower's Falling
is actually based

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:59.490
on a real school
in New York, PS146.

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:04.790
And all the teachers there they
actually saw the towers being

00:04:04.790 --> 00:04:06.830
hit by the airplanes.

00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:09.360
And the teachers
were so traumatized

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:13.880
that they swore they would
never, ever teach the story

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:16.080
of 911 to their students.

00:04:16.080 --> 00:04:19.350
So this book was meant to
have them begin the journey.

00:04:19.350 --> 00:04:21.610
Can you play it for me please?

00:04:21.610 --> 00:04:27.340
[Background Music] It's actually
a mystery story where Deja,

00:04:27.340 --> 00:04:30.230
who is a homeless
African American girl,

00:04:30.230 --> 00:04:34.500
discovers that her father
was a victim of 911.

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:36.240
She doesn't know
that she's homeless

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:39.160
and that he's sick
because of 911.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:41.300
She just feels alienated.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:44.560
But her little brother
says no, we're a family.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:46.750
We're strong together.

00:04:46.750 --> 00:04:50.820
And when she goes to school her
teacher says what are all the

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:53.450
ways in which we're
interconnected?

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:56.970
Just like you are all
interconnected with your family,

00:04:56.970 --> 00:05:01.000
your friends, living in
D.C., going to schools.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.110
And this is my favorite where
Deja says family, friends,

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:09.510
me, we are all Americans.

00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:14.160
Now in school she learns about
how the towers were built.

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:17.980
And she also sees for the
very first time the flames

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:20.040
on her friend Ben's computer.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:24.730
And she and Ben decide we're
going to go to the 911 memorial

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:26.340
and they get on a subway

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:30.510
and there they see what America
is all about, multiethnic,

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:37.340
multireligious, multi-diverse
in all kinds of wonderous ways.

00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:41.960
And at the memorial they see
the footprints of the towers

00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:47.140
and they can imagine the
absence, the ghost towers.

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:54.880
And at the memorial, which I
hope you all get to go see,

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.240
you'll see water falling
down into the footprints,

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:02.730
reaffirming that life
rises, America rises.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:06.490
And there is my splendid
Deja girl, her friend, Ben,

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:10.560
her friend, Sabeen and
her teacher Ms. Garcia.

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:17.140
And this is a book that I urge
you all to read and to talk

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:20.230
to your teachers
and parents about.

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:22.880
So I'm very proud
that I did that book.

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:26.760
And when I got done with this
book my editor said, Jewell,

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:31.640
why don't you write about young
men of color, children younger

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:36.710
than 18 being killed due
to racism and racial bias?

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:38.750
What did I say?

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:41.720
No, no way.

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:45.340
But again I thought about
it and I thought how all

00:06:45.340 --> 00:06:49.000
of you young people are
going to be the change,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:50.970
that all of you have
an opportunity

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:54.270
to make the world a better
place where everyone is judged

00:06:54.270 --> 00:06:56.340
by the content of
their character

00:06:56.340 --> 00:06:58.540
and not the color of their skin.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:01.880
And I remember Emmett
Till being murdered

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.860
when I was just a little girl.

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:05.760
And then I was affected
by the murders

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:08.240
of Tamir Rice and
Trayvon Martin.

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:12.010
And so I created a
character named Gerome.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:17.210
The novel talks about how
everybody needs their story

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:20.910
heard, everybody needs
their story felt.

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:25.330
And that we all connect across
time, that all of you are going

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:29.250
to make the world a better
place for the next generation.

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:33.810
So students, children,
feel your power.

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:38.140
Another part of the novel
is that you can't undo wrong

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:40.360
so bad things do happen.

00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:42.250
So what do we want to do?

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:46.300
Do our best to make
things right.

00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:48.490
Now I want to show you
this wonderous public

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:50.510
service announcement.

