&gt;&gt; And so did theirs.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:00.240
[ Sirens ]

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:01.540
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes: Ghost
Boys talks about yes, applaud.

00:10:01.540 --> 00:10:02.840
It's beautiful.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.140
[applause] It talks
about bearing witness.

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:05.440
And this filmmaker, Kerry Davis,

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:06.740
is bearing witness how
art can make us understand

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:08.040
tragedy better.

00:10:08.040 --> 00:10:09.340
My novel seeks to help us
understand racial bias better

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:10.640
so that children can
help be the change.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:11.940
And in this story there's
a whole crew of ghost boys,

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:13.240
Emmett Till, Trayvon Martin,
Tamir Rice, and the only person

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:15.710
who can see the ghost boys
is Sarah, the daughter

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:18.260
of a white police officer.

00:10:18.260 --> 00:10:21.770
And Sarah is going to be the
one that helps make the change,

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:25.610
that helps make the
world a better place.

00:10:25.610 --> 00:10:31.080
The novel ends with these last
words, Jerome, the ghost boy,

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:37.320
saying, bear witness,
my tale is told.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:42.810
Wake, only the living can
make the world better.

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:45.980
Live and make it better.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:52.380
Don't let me or anyone
else tell this tale again.

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:56.260
Peace out, ghost boy.

00:10:56.260 --> 00:10:59.200
[applause] Thank you,
let's hear some questions.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:02.200
Yay, thank you.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:08.770
Now we can go, oops,
oops, I messed it up.

00:11:08.770 --> 00:11:10.070
Questions?

00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:11.370
Yes, sir?

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:13.960
&gt;&gt; What inspired you
to make Ghost Boys?

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:15.550
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:
You know I am the mother

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:20.460
of a black son and my boy
has the sweetest, warmest,

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:23.310
most wonderful heart
and personality.

00:11:23.310 --> 00:11:27.100
And as he grew older people
would make projections

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:29.140
of stereotypes upon him.

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:31.590
They would see him
in a negative way.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.040
And it just broke my heart.

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:36.830
And I wanted to make a
book that bore witness

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:39.620
that nobody should
ever judge anybody

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:42.040
out of fear, out of prejudice.

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:45.990
And so I'm helping to make
the world better for him.

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:49.360
And I'm hoping you guys will
help make the world better

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:52.180
for all the world's,
other children of color.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:54.950
&gt;&gt; Oh and do you remember me

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:57.760
from the Frederick
Public Library?

00:11:57.760 --> 00:11:59.150
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: Yes, I do.

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:02.130
I can't see as well because
the light is in my face

00:12:02.130 --> 00:12:05.600
but do you know for the kids
who come to see me it's almost

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:09.770
as though your images, your
words, become part of my heart.

00:12:09.770 --> 00:12:14.500
And it's like I have this idea
that when I maybe dying one day

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:18.140
that I'm going to call on all
the images of all the children

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:21.570
that I've ever met and all the
stories they've ever written me

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:23.860
and hold it and press
it close to my heart.

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.160
So thank you.

00:12:25.160 --> 00:12:26.460
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

