&gt;&gt; When you thought of the
idea, how old was your son?

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:42.810
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:
Well how old was my son?

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:44.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:45.510
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: My son is,

00:12:45.510 --> 00:12:48.830
I started writing the
book when he was about 25.

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:51.580
And he's now 28.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.770
And actually he's
studying a Master's

00:12:54.770 --> 00:12:57.290
in nursing program in Baltimore.

00:12:57.290 --> 00:13:01.440
So I'm really, really happy
that he is using his life

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:05.440
to help people who are ill
and to make a difference.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:08.060
But we talk about
race and stereotyping.

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:12.160
We talk about how you can make
a difference by making sure

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:15.720
that you don't become
bitter or so sad.

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:17.590
You have to be triumphant.

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:20.170
You have to live
and make it better

00:13:20.170 --> 00:13:23.290
and believe in that always.

00:13:23.290 --> 00:13:26.100
Right on? Right on.

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:27.830
You're so beautiful.

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:29.130
Yes?

00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:30.430
&gt;&gt; Hi, I have two questions.

00:13:30.430 --> 00:13:31.730
My first one is

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:33.030
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: Is this Mary?

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:34.330
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:13:34.330 --> 00:13:35.630
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: Hi, Mary.

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:36.930
&gt;&gt; My first one is
who inspired you

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:38.230
to be the person you are today?

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:39.530
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: My grandmother.

00:13:39.530 --> 00:13:44.810
My grandmother raised me from
the time I was an infant.

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:46.470
And my grandmother filled me

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:50.010
with so much love
and so much wisdom.

00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:53.620
And she'd say Jewell
everybody in the world is

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.620
as good as anybody else.

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:58.050
We're all a mixed blood stew.

00:13:58.050 --> 00:14:00.500
She'd also say Jewell,
child, do good

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:03.330
and it will fly right
back to you.

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:11.280
And she also said Jewell, child,
wear clean underwear always.

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:12.580
[laughter] The grandmother

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:15.260
on hot summer nights
would tell me stories.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:18.420
And I think she was
the first storyteller

00:14:18.420 --> 00:14:20.620
that really had an impact on me.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:22.890
Now my grandmother in those era,

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:25.390
she never finished
the third grade.

00:14:25.390 --> 00:14:28.750
She didn't know how to
read books or write books.

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:32.310
But she worked hard so that
I could become educated

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:35.480
so that I could read
and write books for you.

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:37.390
But grandmother was the wisest,

00:14:37.390 --> 00:14:39.960
most wonderful woman
I've ever known.

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:42.120
So number two, Mary?

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:45.020
&gt;&gt; My second question
is why was Sarah able

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:46.910
to see Jerome instead of Kim?

00:14:46.910 --> 00:14:48.210
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:51.650
You know the reason why Kim
doesn't need to see Jerome is

00:14:51.650 --> 00:14:55.580
that Kim is very much connected
to her grandmother who believes

00:14:55.580 --> 00:14:59.320
in every good goodbye ain't
gone, that African spirits

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:01.850
and ancestors are
a part of her life.

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:04.380
So Kim knows that
from her grandmother.

00:15:04.380 --> 00:15:07.760
She also now has Carlos,
the young Hispanic guy

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:12.130
who gave Jerome the gun
that caused the incident

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:15.720
to be misconstrued by
the police officer.

00:15:15.720 --> 00:15:19.190
And Carlos has the day
of the dead which is just

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:21.220
like every goodbye ain't gone.

00:15:21.220 --> 00:15:23.620
And he doesn't need
to see Jerome either

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:27.440
because he knows spirits,
the afterlife, the presence

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:30.280
of good souls, are
always with us.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:33.160
But Sarah's tradition,
she didn't have

00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:35.660
that cultural spirit
of tradition.

00:15:35.660 --> 00:15:38.030
She was left without it.

00:15:38.030 --> 00:15:43.610
So Jerome has to teach her, no,
if you live your life believing

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:47.120
that you can bear witness,
that you can honor the dead,

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:48.960
you will live a better life.

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:50.670
So she needs to learn that.

00:15:50.670 --> 00:15:53.980
And that's a way in which
African American heritage,

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:59.330
Hispanic American heritage, all
infuse her as a young white girl

00:15:59.330 --> 00:16:01.370
to make the world
a better place.

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:03.570
I think that's pretty cool.

00:16:03.570 --> 00:16:04.870
Don't you, Mary?

00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:06.170
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:16:06.170 --> 00:16:07.470
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: I do too.

00:16:07.470 --> 00:16:08.770
Good.

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:10.070
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:11.370
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker
Rhodes: Thank you.

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:12.670
Yes sir, oh is it sir or a girl?

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:15.750
I was looking, it's
a girl, I was looking

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:17.980
at the guy behind you.

00:16:17.980 --> 00:16:23.600
&gt;&gt; What gave you the
idea to become a writer?

00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:25.760
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes: You
know I always wrote stories

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:28.660
because my grandmother was
always telling me stories.

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:31.140
But it wasn't until I
was a junior in college

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:34.560
when I saw my first book
written by a black woman author.

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:38.650
And it was like, wow,
black women write books?

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:39.950
I didn't know that.

00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:44.280
I didn't know black men wrote
books or the people from Africa

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.870
or Chile or all over
the world wrote books.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:51.930
But once I discovered that,
once I could see my culture

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.690
in a book I switched
my major to English

00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:58.700
and I started writing
seriously and professionally.

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:01.720
And in particular I fell
in love with Louisiana

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:05.690
which has all kinds
of wonderful ghosts.

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:10.550
&gt;&gt; Because I wanted to tell
you that I write books too.

00:17:10.550 --> 00:17:12.890
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:
You write books too?

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:14.670
I am so proud of you.

00:17:14.670 --> 00:17:17.820
Never doubt for a moment
that because you're young

00:17:17.820 --> 00:17:20.060
that you can't do great work.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:23.490
I know a lot of young writers
who have been published.

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:24.790
There's also a market,

00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:26.810
children's market,
for young writers.

00:17:26.810 --> 00:17:30.090
And they're also online in
print magazines that look

00:17:30.090 --> 00:17:31.770
for young people's writing.

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:35.030
And with my own kids, they went
to a high school for writing

00:17:35.030 --> 00:17:37.110
and there're actually,
did you know scholarships

00:17:37.110 --> 00:17:39.970
to college for writing stories?

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:44.100
So you get a teacher, your
parents, or if you ever want

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:47.530
to you can email me, there
are a lot of opportunities.

00:17:47.530 --> 00:17:50.680
So if you want to go out there
and publish a book I'm going

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:53.270
to be the first one
in line to buy it.

00:17:53.270 --> 00:17:54.570
&gt;&gt; Ok.

00:17:54.570 --> 00:17:55.870
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes: Ok?

00:17:55.870 --> 00:17:57.170
Ok, thank you.

00:17:57.170 --> 00:17:58.940
[applause]

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:02.030
&gt;&gt; What inspired
you to write Sugar?

00:18:02.030 --> 00:18:03.330
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:
Sugar, I have been going

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:12.200
to China every year for about
five years teaching the Chinese

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:14.360
how to do creative writing.

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:18.030
And a friend of mine sent me a
book saying that in Louisiana

00:18:18.030 --> 00:18:21.410
and Mississippi during
reconstruction they brought

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:24.840
in Chinese workers to
work the plantations.

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:29.070
So a lot of African Americans
newly free, they went north,

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:30.960
so they had a labor shortage.

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:34.720
But these Chinese were
treated sometimes as bad

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:36.900
as if they were slaves.

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:40.360
They were treated
just horrifically.

00:18:40.360 --> 00:18:43.520
And so in my story
Sugar is the young woman

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:46.250
who brings together
the Chinese workers

00:18:46.250 --> 00:18:48.400
with the remaining
African workers.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:49.990
She also is the one that reaches

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:52.710
out to the former
master's white son.

00:18:52.710 --> 00:18:56.540
And she brings them all
together in a community of love,

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:58.690
in a community of freedom.

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:02.500
One of the things that I
hadn't really sort of impacted

00:19:02.500 --> 00:19:06.160
or known well was that America
historically has had many

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:09.390
different times or
different immigrant groups

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:11.210
at first might have been welcome

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:13.470
but at other times
was pushed out.

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:15.100
So this enabled me
to tell a story

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:17.420
where the Chinese
were not allowed

00:19:17.420 --> 00:19:19.590
to become American citizens.

00:19:19.590 --> 00:19:21.880
We had the Chinese
Exclusion Act.

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:23.900
And it seemed to me appropriate

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.390
to have a newly freed slave
girl whose filled with the power

00:19:27.390 --> 00:19:30.270
of civil rights wanting
to be there and be friends

00:19:30.270 --> 00:19:33.890
and advocate for
the Chinese as well.

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:37.240
So it was just a happy accident.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:39.120
Anything else?

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:40.610
Yes?

00:19:40.610 --> 00:19:44.440
&gt;&gt; How old were you when
you started writing?

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:47.190
&gt;&gt; Jewell Parker Rhodes:
Probably about seven years old.

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:48.830
And during high school
I wrote a lot

00:19:48.830 --> 00:19:50.960
of poetry and it was terrible.

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:55.950
When I was in high school
I had a big afro, this big.

00:19:55.950 --> 00:19:58.610
And I used to wear
Dashiki's and love beads

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:00.260
and write really bad poetry.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:04.310
It wasn't until I was in
college that I had the chance

00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:08.240
to open a cookbook that told
me about a voodoo queen,

00:20:08.240 --> 00:20:11.020
that told me about the magic
and mystery of New Orleans,

00:20:11.020 --> 00:20:14.560
that I began to just
write from my imagination.

00:20:14.560 --> 00:20:17.180
And it's been a lovely
journey ever since.

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:22.470
But writing for youth, writing
for you, absolutely the best.

00:20:22.470 --> 00:20:25.490
Thank you.

00:20:25.490 --> 00:20:28.410
[applause] Any other questions?

00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:32.720
I've got perhaps maybe two
minutes before I say goodbye

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:34.630
to all of you.

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:38.100
And I want to encourage
all of you young people,

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:41.360
you know when people say I want
to be a writer, how do I do it?

00:20:41.360 --> 00:20:45.900
Well the very first
thing you do is read

00:20:45.900 --> 00:20:47.720
and read and read some more.

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:51.870
Because as you're reading you're
learning about styles and ideas

00:20:51.870 --> 00:20:54.130
and plots and things
that you like.

00:20:54.130 --> 00:20:56.300
And they all go inside you.

00:20:56.300 --> 00:20:57.600
And one day when you start

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:00.780
to write a story you will
actually start drawing

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:02.760
that out of you.

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:05.330
Secondly, never ever believe

00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:08.520
that your experience
isn't worthy of a book.

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:11.280
Everything about you,
everything you do,

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:14.540
everything you will do
can be written in a book

00:21:14.540 --> 00:21:16.540
and shared with someone else.

00:21:16.540 --> 00:21:20.210
It's an act of love, an
act of communication.

00:21:20.210 --> 00:21:22.840
And did you guys know
I'm a grandmother?

00:21:22.840 --> 00:21:26.120
I have Claire, Claire
is two years old.

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:29.770
So you know who Claire
is buying books from?

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:32.250
Maybe all of you guys.

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:33.980
We need you.

00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:36.000
We need diverse books.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.150
We need all stories.

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:43.990
So grow up, read and write
and make the world better.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:45.410
Thank you very much.

00:21:45.410 --> 00:21:46.710
Thank you.

00:21:46.710 --> 00:21:47.940
[applause]

